    "16560502492171dd33": {
      "type": "loop-article-richtext",
      "blocks": {
        "9cf025d1-5938-49bb-88c5-4141d8af1b5c": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Cognitive behavioural therapy (CBT)",
            "heading_size": "h2"
          }
        },
        "76ff5268-049f-4343-93b3-691311723d4c": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>For serious cases of noise sensitivity anxiety, <a href=\"https:\/\/www.nhs.uk\/mental-health\/talking-therapies-medicine-treatments\/talking-therapies-and-counselling\/cognitive-behavioural-therapy-cbt\/overview\/\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">CBT<\/span><\/a> can be an excellent way to change the thought patterns that lead to the anxiety. CBT should always be done under professional guidance and is not an instant fix, but the effects can be life-changing for extreme sufferers of noise-related anxiety.<\/p>"
          }
        },
        "c17791aa-99c0-44b1-9c0e-b600e8c2dd36": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Exposure therapy to reduce your stress response",
            "heading_size": "h2"
          }
        },
        "16560502493ef96db8-0": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>Exposure therapy, either with the help of a professional or simply by gradually exposing yourself to loud noises in a controlled way, can also help you respond less severely to loud situations. To expose yourself to noises, try the following steps:<\/p><p>1. Determine which sound or sounds you are most sensitive to. It could be a specific sound, such as a type of music, coughing, or banging, or it could simply be any noise over a certain volume.<\/p><p>2. Record the noise, or find a recording of it online.<\/p><p>3. Go somewhere comfortable, such as at home on your couch, and try to imagine the sound. Try to familiarize yourself with it and notice if you feel anxiety. Use relaxation techniques if necessary.<\/p><p>4. Once you feel a little more comfortable with the sound, try listening to the recording of it at a low volume. It’s likely that you’ll feel anxious, so take it slowly.<\/p><p>5. Practice relaxation techniques (such as meditation and breathing techniques) to manage your anxiety levels if they start to rise.<\/p><p>6. Increase the volume of the recording as you become more used to it.<\/p><p>7. Repeat this at regular intervals, for example daily, or as often as you can manage. Over time, your response should start to become less intense.<\/p>"
          }
        }
      },
